In [17]:
# Create function that uses adfuller test

def ad_fuller(dataset):
    print('ADF Test:')
    adftest = adfuller(dataset)
    adfoutput = pd.Series(adftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic','p-value','Lags Used','No. of Observations'])
    for key, value in adftest[4].items():
        adfoutput['Critical Value (%s)' %(key)] = value
    print(adfoutput)

ad_fuller(ts_train)

ADF Test:

p-value                   0.982761

No. of Observations     483.000000

Critical Value (5%)      -2.867543

P value indicates that our series is not stationary. >0.05 so we fail to reject the null hypothesis: series is non-stationary.

Log transformation doesn't help. There's still a trend to the rolling mean so we need to apply a shift and see if that works. The series does have constant variance though.

ADF test confirms what we see visually with a p-value>0.05 we fail to reject the null hypothesis and the series is non-stationary.

In [19]:
# Try shifted series

ts_shift = ts_log-ts_log.shift(periods = 1)
mavg_shift = ts_shift.rolling(window = 12).mean()
mstd_shift = ts_shift.rolling(window = 12).std()
ts_shift = ts_shift.fillna(0) # Replace 1st difference with 0
plt.figure(figsize=(16,8))
plt.plot(ts_shift, color = 'c', label = "Shifted Series (Order 1)")
plt.plot(mavg_shift, color = 'red', label = "Moving Avg")
plt.plot(mstd_shift, color = 'green', label = "Rolling StDev")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Visually it looks like the shifted series has constant mean and variance. We'll test this with ADF test.

Plotting ACF and PACF to optimize SARIMAX model

In [22]:
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf,plot_pacf

plt.figure(figsize = (16,8))
plot_acf(ts_shift, lags = 24) 
plt.show() 
plot_pacf(ts_shift, lags = 24) 
plt.show()

<Figure size 1152x576 with 0 Axes>

From the PACF plot we see that the highest lag at which the plot extends beyond the statistically significant boundary is lag 1. Therefore in AR models we will use a lag of 1.

From the ACF plot, we infer that q=1; first lag for which the ACF crosses the upper confidence interval.

We also note autocorrelation at lags 12 and 24. This indicates annual seasonality which we'll use in our SARIMAX model.

Note: we have chosen not to include prior models in our final submission. We rejected AR, MA, and ARIMA models, and do not include them in this analysis (they are available in prior submissions).

Previous models are unable to cope with the extreme seasonality of the data (these are not included here as they do not form a part of our final submission). SARIMAX is able to do so to some extent.

Still, the model doesn't fit the train data very well, and equally it doesn't fit the test data very well.

One thing we can try is a grid search of SARIMAX parameters.

In [30]:
# Grid search to tune SARIMAX hyperparameters


p_list = range(0,3)
d_list = range(0,3)
q_list = range(0,3)

model_results=[]
for p in p_list:
    for d in d_list:
        for q in q_list:
            model_SARIMAX = SARIMAX(ts_shift, order=(1,1,1), seasonal_order=(p,d,q,12))
            results_SARIMAX = model_SARIMAX.fit(disp=False)
            model_results.append([mean_squared_error(results_SARIMAX.fittedvalues,ts_shift['Value'], squared = False),p,d,q])

We used grid search with various parameter combinations to optimize the SARIMAX model.

However, we see that our default choice of p,d,q = 1 is close to optimal-grid search does not confer any meaningful advantage.

Overall, the SARIMAX model is our best fit so far, but is not a very good fit.

We will try Prophet-an additive model specifically designed to handle extremely seasonal data.

In [32]:
from prophet import Prophet

prophet_model = Prophet()
ts_train_prophet_format=ts_train.copy(deep=True)
ts_train_prophet_format["ds"]=ts_train_prophet_format.index
ts_train_prophet_format.rename(columns={"Value":"y"}, inplace=True)
prophet_model.fit(ts_train_prophet_format) # Fit Prophet on training data
future = prophet_model.make_future_dataframe(periods=24, freq="MS")
forecast_prophet = prophet_model.predict(future)
forecast_df_prophet = forecast_prophet[['ds', 'yhat']]
forecast_df_prophet.index=forecast_df_prophet['ds']
forecast_df_prophet.drop(columns=['ds'], inplace=True)

Prophet provides a good fit, as we can see visually. RMSE is significantly lower on training and test data than it is for SARIMAX, our next-best-fitting model.

This is the best of all models we've used so far, and will feature in our final submission.
